# Daily Summary

## 2026-06-11

Today we moved Resrva further from a single-venue booking tool toward a multi-client, multi-venue platform.

### Multi-client and venue setup

- Added the owner/admin direction for managing clients separately from venue managers.
- Clarified the model:
  - Resrva owner manages clients.
  - Each client owns one or more venues.
  - Venue managers should only see their own venue data.
- Added/adjusted client and venue management flows so venues can be created and accessed through slug-style URLs such as `/old-canberra-inn`.
- Tightened the idea that bookings, tables, areas, settings, booking types, and calendar data should be scoped per venue/client.

### Booking types

- Continued building the flexible booking type system for dining, functions, events, and custom types.
- Added booking type delete support.
  - If unused, the type can be removed.
  - If historical bookings exist, it is archived instead so past data stays intact.
- Moved delete into Additional Settings.
- Replaced browser confirmation popups with an in-app modal pattern.
- Added icon picker behavior and made booking type icons show in relevant admin lists.
- Continued refining booking type settings:
  - Event end time.
  - Booking duration.
  - Booking window.
  - Multiple weekly days.
  - Daily, weekly, fortnightly, monthly, custom, and no-repeat scheduling.
  - Custom date selection through a calendar-style flow.
- Removed confusing/duplicated rules like separate approval and auto-confirm toggles, moving toward a single Auto Confirmation setting.

### Booking page

- Kept booking type identity out of the booking table rows.
- Restored the original table/area behavior:
  - Main row shows the assigned table.
  - Area shows underneath.
  - No booking type tag/text appears in the table cell.
- Added event booking table assignment behavior so event bookings can be assigned to tables like normal bookings.
- Adjusted event booking availability so reserved event areas can affect table assignment.
- Group headers can still use booking type identity, but row-level booking data stays focused on the actual booking/table details.

### Calendar

- Added event/function indicators to the calendar view.
- Kept tags in the same compact row style as the existing Off tag.
- Changed Function display to use the generic label `Function` instead of showing individual function type names.
- Made calendar function/event tags use the configured booking type colour where appropriate.

### Tables and areas

- Removed old function-area scheduling logic from the tables/areas page because event/function area reservation now belongs with booking types.
- Split the reserved area idea away from generic table/area management.
- Continued shaping the logic so functions/events can reserve areas while individual bookings can still be assigned tables.

### Settings and auto-assignment

- Started reshaping the settings page toward the same breadcrumb-style format used on Booking Types.
- Discussed and refined the auto-assignment direction:
  - Avoid manager-heavy manual join-group setup.
  - Prefer sensible defaults such as using the fewest suitable tables and adjacent tables when combining is required.
  - Move away from visible assignment style toggles.
  - Longer-term direction is a learning assignment system that adapts from manager corrections and historical behavior per venue/client.

### Booking type colours

- Centralised booking type colour handling in the frontend.
- Booking type colour now feeds shared booking-type UI surfaces instead of each page hand-rolling its own colour logic.
- Updated booking type colour usage across:
  - Booking group identity styling.
  - Calendar event/function tags.
  - Dashboard booking type badges.
  - Public booking service/session selectors.
- Reverted booking/guest count pills back to neutral grey because those are metadata counts, not booking type identity.

### Quality checks

